If your home or business has been flooded:

  • Have all electrical and gas equipment professionally tested before use.
  • Clean and dry out the building as soon as possible.

Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. For emergency assistance from the SES call 132 500.

This Flood Watch is being issued for Latrobe River.

Widespread minor flooding with isolated moderate and major flooding is occurring for parts of the Flood Watch area.   

A slow moving low pressure system is moving eastwards across the State during Monday. Widespread rainfall across the Flood Watch area has caused minor flooding, with isolated moderate and major flooding. The system is forecast to move out over the Tasman Sea early Tuesday. 

In the 24 hours to 9:00 am Monday, rainfall totals up to 181 mm were observed across parts of the Flood Watch area. Catchments are moderately wet following recent rainfall. 

Widespread rainfall totals of 25 to 60 mm are likely across north central and north eastern catchments of the Flood Watch area for the remainder of Monday. Higher isolated totals are possible due to heavy falls from thunderstorms. 

Rainfall will ease and showers are expected to gradually contract to the east of the state during Tuesday. River level rises and widespread minor flooding with isolated moderate to major flooding is likely to continue during the remainder of Monday and into Tuesday for parts of the Northern Flood Watch catchments.

River level rises and widespread minor flooding is likely to occur for parts of the Gippsland and Central Flood Watch catchments.

Flooding may continue to develop in catchments throughout the Flood Watch area. 
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • Stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.

properties.name: Emergency Warning
properties.webBody:
This Emergency Warning is being issued for low lying parts of Seymour . 

Just below Major level flooding is being experienced in the low lying parts of Seymour.
River levels in Seymour are now starting to slowly fall below the Major flood level, and at 8pm tonight was , reading 6.52 m at the Seymour gauge. Slightly below the 1993 flood peak (6.65 m).

Even though river levels have fallen slightly, if you live, work or are holidaying in the streets listed, you should still Evacuate Immediately. 
  • Deep Floodwaters are very slowly falling so there is no risk of a return to the higher flood levels than was experienced earlier today.
  • Community members should take great care when evacuating and moving around in the dark.
Flooding is expected to impact the following streets:
  • Emily Street, Tierney Street, Lesley Street, Tallarook Street, Wallis Street, High Street, Elizabeth Street, Butler Street, Alexander Street, Edward Street, Station Street, Tristan Street, Hanna Street, Jubilee Street, Industrial Court.
  • Kings Park and local river caravan parks will be impacted.
Initial Ground Observer reports indicate that:
  • No inhabited homes have been flooded above floor level, however a small number of businesses have been impacted by overfloor flooding. Some uninhabited homes previously damaged in the Oct 2022 flood have been flooded again.
  • Local streets in the listed low lying area will experience backflow along local drains, this happens in floods.
If you are located in the area listed above, it is recommended you Evacuate Immediately.
What you should do: 

Check out the Seymour Local Flood Guide for more detailed information: https://www.ses.vic.gov.au/plan-and-stay-safe/flood-guides/mitchell-shire-council

Travel to a safe location. Options include: 
  • A Relief Centre that has been opened at Seymour Sports & Aquatic Centre at Chittick Park. 
  • Family or friends’ homes located in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • The safest evacuation route is via Anzac Avenue to Chittick Park.
When you leave, remember to take your pets, mobile phone and medications. 

Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 

If you are travelling by car: 
  • Do not drive through floodwater. 
  • Find alternative travel routes if roads or underpasses are flooded. 
  • Be aware of driving hazards, such as mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees. 
  • If driving conditions are dangerous, safely pull over away from trees, drains, low lying areas and floodwater. 
If you stay: 
  • If you choose to stay, emergency services may not be able to help you. 
  • Stay inside and be aware of changing conditions. 
  • If floodwater comes inside, move to a higher point such as a kitchen bench or second story. 
  • Follow your emergency plan, if you have one. 
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation, if safe to do so. 
This warning is current to 6.00pm Monday January 8, 2024. If you do not evacuate before this time, your property may be isolated or inundated with water and it may be too late to leave. 

You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. 

For emergency assistance from the SES, call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur. 
  • Evacuating too late or choosing to remain in your home when recommended to evacuate is dangerous and may put your life at risk.
Key access roads likely to be affected by flooding include:
  • Alexander Street, Bolton Street, Edward Street, Elizabeth Street, Emily Street East and West, Goulburn Valley Highway, High Street, Lesley Street, Moody Street, Robert Street, Station Street, Tallarook Street, Tierney Street, Wallis Street and William Street.
  • Kings Park and local river caravan parks will be impacted.

This Emergency Warning is being issued for low lying parts of Seymour . 

Just below Major level flooding is being experienced in the low lying parts of  Seymour.
River levels in Seymour are now starting to slowly fall below the Major flood level, and at 8pm tonight was , reading 6.52 m at the Seymour gauge. Slightly below the 1993 flood peak (6.65 m).

- Local streets in the listed low lying area will experience backflow along local drains, this happens in floods.


        If you are located in the area listed above, it is   recommended you Evacuate Immediately.

This Watch and Act message replaces the Major flood warning issued at 12.06 am today. 

MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING AT SEYMOUR
MAJOR FLOODING POSSIBLE AT MURCHISON OVERNIGHT TUESDAY INTO WEDNESDAY
MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE AT SHEPPARTON OVERNIGHT WEDNESDAY INTO THURSDAY

  • Rainfall totals of up to 40 mm have been recorded in parts of the Goulburn catchment since 9:00am Monday. No significant rainfall has been forecast for Tuesday.
  • Releases from Lake Eildon are currently at 1000 ML/day.
Goulburn River Lake Eildon to Seymour:
  • Moderate flooding is likely along the Goulburn River Lake Eildon to Seymour. 
  • Minor flooding is occurring along the Goulburn River at Trawool.
  • The Goulburn River downstream of Lake Eildon is currently at 1.11 metres and steady, below the minor flood level (3.00 m). 
  • The Goulburn River downstream of  Lake Eildon is expected to remain below the minor flood level (3.00 m).
  • The Goulburn River at Seymour peaked at 6.80 metres around 04:00 pm Monday 08 January and is currently at 6.07 metres and falling, with moderate flooding. 
  • A renewed rise is expected along the Goulburn River at Seymour during Tuesday morning. The river may peak near 6.50 metres Tuesday morning, with moderate flooding.
Act now - take actions immediately to protect your life and property, and move to higher ground.
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 
  • Check out the SES Seymour Local Flood Guide for more detailed information: https://www.ses.vic.gov.au/plan-and-stay-safe/flood-guides/mitchell-shire-council
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.

  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Goulburn River Murchison to Shepparton.
This Watch and Act message replaces the warning issued at 2.08 am this morning.

MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE AT SHEPPARTON OVERNIGHT WEDNESDAY INTO THURSDAY
MAJOR FLOODING POSSIBLE AT MURCHISON OVERNIGHT TUESDAY INTO WEDNESDAY
MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING AT SEYMOUR

  • Rainfall totals of up to 40 mm have been recorded in parts of the Goulburn catchment since 9:00am Monday. 
  • No significant rainfall has been forecast for Tuesday.
  • Releases from Lake Eildon are currently at 1000 ML/day.

Goulburn River at Shepparton 
  • Is currently at 5.17 metres and steady, below the minor flood level.
  • The Goulburn River at Shepparton is likely to exceed the minor flood level (9.50 m) Wednesday afternoon. 
  • The river level may reach the moderate flood level (10.70 m) overnight Wednesday into Thursday. 
  • Further rises are possible as upstream flood waters arrive.
Goulburn River Seymour to Murchison
  • Major flooding may occur along the Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton.
  • The Goulburn River at Murchison is currently at 7.91 metres and rising, below the minor flood level. The Goulburn River at Murchison is likely to exceed the minor flood level (9.00 m) Tuesday morning. 
  • The river level is likely to exceed the moderate flood level (10.20 m) Tuesday afternoon and may reach the major flood level (10.70 m) overnight Tuesday into Wednesday.

Prepare for flooding now. 
Take actions to protect your life and property against potential hazards caused by flooding.
What you should do:

  • Check out the NEW SES Shepparton-Mooroopna-Kialla Local Flood Guide for more detailed information: https://www.ses.vic.gov.au/plan-and-stay-safe/flood-guides/greater-shepparton-city-council
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Rising floodwater can be dangerous. Be aware of water levels rising near you.
  • Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one.
  • Be prepared to move household items to higher ground, on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 
  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground.
If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.

If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations. A small number of properties are likely to be impacted and possibility become isolated.
  • Check out the NEW SES Shepparton-Mooroopna-Kialla Local Flood Guide for more detailed information: https://www.ses.vic.gov.au/plan-and-stay-safe/flood-guides/greater-shepparton-city-council
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding. Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
At Moderate flood level 10.70 m :
  • Watt Road and Raftery Road will have started to flood.

This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Goulburn River Seymour to Murchison.
This Watch and Act for Major flooding message replaces the warning issued at 2.09 am this morning.

MAJOR FLOODING POSSIBLE AT MURCHISON OVERNIGHT TUESDAY INTO WEDNESDAY
MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE AT SHEPPARTON OVERNIGHT WEDNESDAY INTO THURSDAY
MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING AT SEYMOUR

  • Rainfall totals of up to 40 mm have been recorded in parts of the Goulburn catchment since 9:00am Monday. 
  • No significant rainfall has been forecast for Tuesday.
  • Releases from Lake Eildon are currently at 1000 ML/day.
Goulburn River Seymour to Murchison
  • Major flooding may occur along the Goulburn River Seymour to Murchison.
  • The Goulburn River at Murchison is currently at 7.91 metres and rising, below the minor flood level. The Goulburn River at Murchison is likely to exceed the minor flood level (9.00 m) Tuesday morning. 
  • The river level is likely to exceed the moderate flood level (10.20 m) Tuesday afternoon and may reach the major flood level (10.70 m) overnight Tuesday into Wednesday.
Goulburn River Murchison to Shepparton
  • The Goulburn River at Shepparton is currently at 5.17 metres and steady, below the minor flood level. 
  • The Goulburn River at Shepparton is likely to exceed the minor flood level (9.50 m) Wednesday afternoon. 
  • The river level may reach the moderate flood level (10.70 m) overnight Wednesday into Thursday. 
  • Further rises are possible as upstream flood waters arrive.
Move to higher ground. 
Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
  • Rising floodwater can be dangerous. Be aware of water levels rising near you.
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary.
  • Check out the SES Murchison Local Flood Guide for more flood information: https://www.ses.vic.gov.au/plan-and-stay-safe/flood-guides/greater-shepparton-city-council
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground, if still safe to do.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, well away from waterways. 

If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.     
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations. 
  • Evacuation of some houses may be required.
  • A small number of properties are likely to be impacted and possibly become isolated in the Old Weir Road area.
  •  Low-lying rural properties upstream and downstream of Murchison likely to be flooded which may require the moving of stock and equipment to higher ground and the closure of some local roads and the Campbells Bend camping and fishing spots north of the Bridge.
  • At 10.15 m, during the 2010 flood, the River Haven caravan park residents and caravans were relocated to higher ground.
Road Closures:
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
  • For more information on road closures go to traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
  • The Bendigo-Murchison Rd i( C 375) is closed between Colbinabbin and Rushworth, speed limits are also in place along this road due to road surface damage west of the Cattanach Canal
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 09/01/2024 07:30 am or as the situation changes.

  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Lifeline on www.lifeline.org.au or phone 13 11 14. Beyond Blue on www.beyondblue.org.au or phone 1300 224 636. Kids Helpine on www.kidshelp.com.au or phone 1800 551 800. SANE Australia on www.sane.org or phone 1800 187 263.

properties.webBody:
This Advice is being issued for Poowong, Loch and Nyora residents. 
  • The tap water in Poowong, Loch and Nyora is not safe to drink without boiling first. 
  • A boil water advisory has been issued following reports of contaminated water in the Poowong-Loch-Nyora water supply system.
  • Consumption of unboiled water can cause gastro-like symptoms. If you experience any of these symptoms, please contact your GP and inform your GP of this advisory.
  • This is an updated Advice message that replaces the Advice issued at 9:53 am on Friday 5 January 2024.
If you live or work within Poowong, Loch and Nyora, you must boil tap water before drinking. Or drink bottled water.
What you should do:  
  • Boil water before drinking it, or drink bottled water.  
  • Boil water for washing and preparing food, preparing beverages, making ice and for preparing baby formula. 
  • Boil water for brushing teeth.
To ensure water is safe to drink you should: 
  • Heat water until a continuous and rapid stream of air-bubbles is produced from the bottom of a pan or kettle (kettles with automatic shut-off switches are suitable, variable temperature kettles should be set to boil).
  • Allow water to cool before use.
  • Store water in a clean, closed container for later use.
  • Be careful when boiling water to prevent scalding or burns. 
It is safe to use unboiled water for:
  • Washing your hands
  • Cleaning dishes - use hot soapy water and let them air dry before using them again or use a dishwasher. 
  • Washing clothes.
  • Showering and bathing in. Young children should be given a sponge bath to avoid them accidentally swallowing the water. 
  • Garden watering. If you grow fruits and vegetables then they will need to be washed with cooled boiled water before you eat them.
  • Flushing toilets.
For health advice:
  • Call Nurse on Call on 1300 60 60 24 or see your doctor if you require medical advice.
Impacts in your area: 
  • South Gippsland Water advises customers in Poowong, Loch and Nyora to boil their drinking water until further notice. 
  • Water trailers are available at Nyora Recreational Reserve, Poowong Recreational Reserve, Main Street Loch and Speight Street in Loch from 9:30 am on 04/01/2024.
  • Further details can be found at https://www.sgwater.com.au/alerts

This Emergency Warning replaces the Too late to leave warning issued at 7 pm tonight.

properties.name: Community Information
properties.webBody:
This message is being issued for water quality at Lake Bolac. 
  • High levels of blue-green algae have been detected in the lake. 
  • The algal bloom is expected to remain until there is significant rainfall to flush the lake or cooler conditions slow the algae. 
  • Regular testing is being conducted to identify new outbreaks or changes that might indicate improved water quality. 
  • This notification will be reviewed weekly and updated as the situation changes.
Warning signs have been installed at the lake.

You should avoid direct contact with affected water in Lake Bolac.

Do not swim in affected areas or use water for cooking, drinking, washing or showering. Boiling the water will not make it safe. 
What you should do:
  • Visit Parks Victoria website (https://www.parks.vic.gov.au/places-to-see/parks/lake-bolac-highway-park) for more information. 
  • Observe information signs posted at the lake.
Protect your health:
  • Direct contact with water affected by blue green algae can cause skin irritation, sore eyes, ears and nose. If swallowed it can cause cramps, nausea and vomiting. 
  • If you do come into contact with affected water, wash your skin immediately in clean cool water. 
  • Boiling affected water does not make it safe to drink. Boiling water bursts the blue green algae cells and releases toxins into the water making it more likely that you will experience symptoms. 
  • If you are experiencing any health issues after contact with affected water seek medical advice from your local doctor or Nurse-On-Call on 1300 60 60 24.
Protect your pets:
  • Pet owners should prevent pets from drinking or having direct contact with contaminated water. 
Agriculture information: 
  • Irrigation water contaminated with blue-green algae should not be spray irrigated on vegetables and fruit, or come in contact with plants being grown for food during processing and packing. 
  • Fruit and vegetables grown in the affected areas are safe to consume if farmers follow recommendations regarding blue-green algae
Impacts in your area:
  • The water is  green as a result of the algae bloom.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Campaspe River downstream of Rochester.

  • Moderate flooding is occurring at Rochester Syphon
Act now - take actions immediately to protect your life and property, and move to higher ground.
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:  
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.

This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Campaspe River - Barnadown to Rochester.
  • MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT ROCHESTER TOWN, FLOOD PEAK MID-MORNING TUESDAY
  • Rainfall eased during Monday, with no further heavy rain forecast
  • The river level at Barnadown has fallen below the minor flood level. A major flood peak passed through Campaspe Weir early Tuesday morning. The major flood peak is expected mid-morning Tuesday at Rochester Town.
  • The situation is being monitored and warnings will be updated regularly.
  • Major flooding is occurring along the Campaspe River from Barnadown to Rochester. Major flooding is occurring at Campaspe Weir.
  • The Campaspe River at Rochester Town is currently at 114.51 mAHD and rising, with major flooding. The Campaspe River at Rochester Town may peak near 114.80 metres mid-morning Tuesday, with major flooding.
  • This Watch and Act message replaces the Watch and Act message issued Tuesday 9 January 2024 at 3.06am 
  • There are a number of major roads in the area that will have been impacted by floodwater, as it recedes please note road surface conditions may have changed.
  • Multiple roads have been closed due to floodwater. The Midland Highway from Huntly to Elmore still remains closed. Before travelling please check information on road closures by visiting traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.   
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations. 
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
  • You may lose services including power, water, sewerage and telephone due to flooding.
  • Evacuation of some houses may be required.
